easingly unsatisfactory, accounts. Dombrowski surveys the classical theists and their roots in ancient Greek philosophy before turning to contributions from the sixteenth through twentieth centuries, ultimately discussing twenty-three thinkers. The key figures in this history are Plato, who ironically provided the philosophical basis both for classical and neoclassical concepts, and three great figures in process theism: Henri Bergson, Alfred North Whitehead, and Hartshorne. The concept of God has a rich past; this book argues that it can have a rich future as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aGodxHistory of doctrines. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Religion. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Process Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Theology. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845938740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438459387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438459387/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles